{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58d712d8-ec8c-4e16-be9d-223437c4d4e6","content":"Here's a concise approach for collecting a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already in the image):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find the process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Analyze** it in Visual Studio (**File → Open**) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview).\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container, you can use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection without modifying the app container. See the [dotnet-monitor docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2673ce0b-cade-4330-b311-00bf241a8350","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":390},"id":"396d23ab-78dd-4cf6-ae4b-97908f146928","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:48:26.923Z","parentId":"49223257-be21-4534-bd1c-0fe73060d3d5"}
